english:
  title: A Letter to Minister Jeong Jeon
  author: Choe Chi-won
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I humbly observe the imperial decree issued on the sixth day of the second month. Your Excellency now holds the station of Hong-bu, illuminating the sage-king's virtue, overseeing the Twin Bureaus while governing the Plumb of State. All people, near and far, dance and leap with joy.

    I humbly reflect that Your Excellency's noble character and illustrious deeds, your great talent and profound learning, have spread through the mouths of all people in the four quarters and poured into the heart of the Ten-Thousand-Chariot Ruler. Indeed, such praise requires no embellishment—only our deepening reverence.

    Moreover, since bandits gathered in the Central Region and troops encamped in Qi-xia, you have led all princes with extraordinary strategy. Thus your talents reached the Dragon Chariot itself, and you ascended to the Hall of the Phoenix. Having traversed distant mountains and rivers, you secured the favor of the Nine Heavens; having conquered the waters and soil, you rose to the hundred days of glory.

    The Bamboo Palace is now entrusted to pure principles, and the Hall of Letters returns to noble aspirations. Thus Sun Shu'ao's careful guardianship grows more reverent with each honor, and Hu Bo-shi's successive advancements follow proper order and purpose. Forever relying on supreme virtue, we await the restoration of the realm. May the Father of the Nation wield the whip, the Marquis of Can hold the bridle—driving the teeming multitudes into the domain of perfect peace, and guiding the barbarian peoples back to the way of Yao and Shun.

    I have long known of your excellence from afar and received your distant blessing through prostration. Yet lacking the means to offer proper congratulations, my shame grows ever deeper.
  footnotes:
    - 'Hong-bu (宏父): An honorific title referring to a statesman of great virtue and wisdom, alluding to figures of antiquity.'
    - 'Twin Bureaus (蘭臺): Administrative offices of high rank overseeing state affairs.'
    - 'The Phoenix Hall and Dragon Chariot: References to imperial favor and advancement to high office.'
    - 'Sun Shu''ao and Hu Bo-shi: Ancient Chinese statesmen exemplifying virtue and wisdom in governance.'
    - 'Yao and Shun: Legendary sage-kings of ancient China, representing ideal rule.'
